.The data were corrected for background by subtracting
sample-out spectra. Corrections were also applied for
finite sample-size effects and for background caused
by parasitic and target-scattered neutrons. The finite
sample-size effects were determined using the Monte
Carlo code SYNTHIA.
The scattered neutrons were detected by a NE213
liquid scintillation detector, 14 cm in diameter and
10 cm thick, located in a massive shield on a rotating
table. The shield could be positioned at angles from
0 to 160 degrees and provide flight paths of 4 to 7 m.
The flight path was 6.5 m for 14.1 MeV and 4 m for 18
MeV measurements. The relative detector efficiency was
determined below 4 MeV by measuring the time-of-flight
spectrum of fission neutrons from a Cf-252 source. At
higher energies the efficiency was calculated using
the code O5S.
A 5 cm diameter by 5 cm thick NE213 detector
was used for normalization of different runs, and for
monitoring time-correlated background neutrons.
One standard deviation.
Error of the experimental data was estimated by
quadratic sum of each error source:
(1) counting statistics (1.% - 30.%),
absolute normalization (5%),
(3) data correction for sample-dependent effects
(10% of the correction).
Tohoku University 4.5 MV Dynamitron
time-of-flight spectrometer.
The 14.1 and 18.0 MeV neutrons were produced
using the T-D reaction at emission angles of 97.5
degrees and 0 degrees, respectively. A Ti-T metallic
target was bombarded by a pulsed deuteron beam with
about 1.5 ns pulse duration.
The neutron energies were determined using
time-of-flight techniques.
Flight path 6 m for 14 MeV energy, 4 m for 18 MeV.
Neutrons and gamma-rays were separated using
pulse-shape discrimination techniques. The dynamic
range was maximized by using two psd systems with
different bias setting.
Absolute double differential
cross sections were determined by comparison with
differential NP scattering cross section, using
polyethylene sample.
.The scattering samples were metallic cylinders of
natural Nb-93 and Bi-209, 3 cm diameter and 5 cm
long. The samples were placed 12 cm from the target.
The polyethylene sample was 1.5-cm diam and 5-cm long.

The laboratory double differential data DDX
corrected for sample-dependent effects were transformed
into the center-of-mass system assuming two body
reaction kinematics to derive energy and angular
distributions in CMS. The energy distributions were
obtained by fitting the DDX in CMS with the Legendre
polynomials. The present energy distributions for the
elastic-scattering do not include the contributions
from the angles between 0 deg and 25 deg because of too
steep angular distributions to make angle-integration.
